📘 Project Overview and Scenario
This Digital Literacy project is designed to develop awareness and practical understanding of responsible and 
safe use of digital technologies among students. The project is based on the scenario of a student acting as
a “Digital Ambassador,” whose role is to guide peers in navigating the digital world effectively and securely.
Through a series of structured tasks, the project covers important aspects of digital literacy, including online
safety, phishing and UPI fraud awareness, responsible social media usage, digital communication etiquette, and the 
use of modern tools such as Google Forms, Canva, GitHub, and HackerRank. Each task focuses on building both theoretical
knowledge and practical skills, such as creating quizzes, designing infographics, writing professional emails, and analysing real-world cybercrime cases.
The overall objective of this project is to equip students with essential digital skills, promote safe online
behavior, and prepare them for academic, professional, and everyday digital interactions in an increasingly technology-driven world.

A situation where poor digital communication caused a real problem can be seen in a group project scenario. One
team member shared important instructions through a short and unclear message in a group chat. The message lacked
proper details about the task division and deadlines, which led to confusion among the team members. As a result,
some students worked on the same part while others missed their tasks completely, causing delays and affecting the
overall quality of the project.
This issue could have been avoided if the communication was clear, structured, and complete. The sender should have
used proper formatting, clearly mentioned roles and deadlines, and confirmed whether everyone understood the 
instructions. Additionally, using a shared document or email for detailed communication would have ensured better coordination and reduced misunderstandings.

